parameters: Section Chief: ──...

Section Chief: You saw them too, didn't you? When you passed
by here earlier. The faces of the people here.

Section Chief: The circumstances of those thrown in here
vary greatly.

Section Chief: There are those who were thrown in here to
work because they couldn't pay back the money they borrowed.
That's still on the better side of things.

Section Chief: It's an everyday occurrence for people to be
brought here half-dead as punishment for jobs that can't be
made public.

Section Chief: Some were sold here at a young age just for a
small amount of money.

Section Chief: There are even those who were captured by
bandits without any fault of their own and sold here to make
money for them. It's a terrible story.

Section Chief: Well, judging by your appearance, you're
probably one of them...

Section Chief: I don't even know who's running this place,
but it's like the dirty parts of humanity have solidified
here.
Section Chief: No one comes here because they want to.

Section Chief: That's why it's a rule here not to ask about
other people's circumstances recklessly.
I understand the situation.

I'll ask about the place instead. What's the purpose of this
mining shaft?

The fact that they're securing labor so cheaply is
nauseating, but I understand.

I've heard that there are mining tunnels operating without
the country's permission, though they shouldn't exist. Do
they produce some rare ore?

But even so, the treatment of the workers is terrible.
They're confined in holes without even creating a
settlement-like place outside.

And what about those heavy iron bars? The excessive guards.
It's as if they're isolating everything from the outside
world, like it would be inconvenient if any information
leaked out.

The workers being forced to labor seem to be working just to
get through the pain without any motivation...

Section Chief: What good does knowing that do you? There's
no need for us to know.

Section Chief: It's rare for someone to stay sane here until
they've finished paying off their own debts. Most die before
they can achieve their goals.

Section Chief: Even if you get out of here, there's no
guarantee you'll be safe. This is that kind of place.
Holding onto hope is just going to make you feel empty.

But that doesn't mean we're digging holes meaninglessly,
right?

Section Chief: Well, it's not like we're being made to do
this without any purpose. There is something we've been told
to do.
Section Chief: Wait a moment.
Section Chief: Here it is.

Section Chief: This is just a small fragment, but yeah,
we're being made to dig endlessly here because of this
thing.
Hmm. This is...

I'm not confident in my knowledge of minerals, but at least
I haven't seen this ore on the market before.

(It doesn't look particularly valuable at first glance. But
even this small piece seems to contain a significant amount
of magical power. That's what intrigues me...)

Section Chief: I don't know the details either. All I know
is that it seems to be worth much more than any of us here.
You shouldn't put yourself down so much.

Everyone may have their own circumstances, but this
environment isn't acceptable for any reason.

Don't let the foul words make you believe you're worthless.
At the very least, you've been kind to me.

Section Chief: You must have had a rough time getting here,
yet you're so naive, or rather, it seems like you're not
used to being deceived by others.

Section Chief: Don't get me wrong. It's rare to find someone
who can talk properly here, so I just ended up talking too
much, that's all.

Section Chief: Look, your hands have stopped again. If you
have time to chat, then give digging another go.
Ah, right...!
